From f59c4e715b60855e5a253e8a55c101f578e66ff2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Apr 2026 17:51:42 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Icon modernization: emoji removal, thin strokes, neutral
 badges
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Outside-audit cleanup. Three coordinated visual changes to bring
iconography and badge styling into line with a more Apple-minimalist
feel and the brand palette (teal/cobalt/navy).

Three problems this fixes:

  1. Landing page used literal emoji (📋 🏗️ 💼) rendered at 36px as
     the user-type card icons. This is actual clip art — full-color
     OS-native, renders differently on Mac/Windows/Android/iOS, and
     sets a 'quick MVP' tone on the very first impression.

  2. Lucide icons across the app rendered at 2px stroke weight.
     Functionally fine, but reads heavier than the Apple SF Symbols
     feel the brand aims for.

  3. Role and status badges used 5 different color families
     (bg-purple-50, bg-blue-50, bg-emerald-50, bg-amber-50, bg-red-50)
     for semantic meaning. Reads as 'stock admin template rainbow'
     rather than brand-aligned. 19+ sites affected across Members,
     Applications, and dashboard surfaces.

Three foundational files added:

  - src/components/Icon.jsx — wrapper around lucide components that
    sets strokeWidth={1.5} default. Call sites change from <Users />
    to <Icon as={Users} /> to get the lighter stroke. Naming note:
    'Icon' clashes with 'const Icon = item.icon' patterns common in
    lucide map-iteration code; this PR renames those locals
    (ItemIcon, StatIcon) at every site. A future refactor could
    rename the wrapper to LucideIcon to avoid the collision.

  - src/lib/roleStyles.js — shared ROLE_DOT_COLORS and
    STATUS_DOT_COLORS maps. Colors pulled from the brand palette
    (teal/cobalt/navy/gray/amber). Notably: 'rejected' status uses
    gray, not red — the label carries the semantic weight, the dot
    just needs to be distinct from 'approved'. Red dots on a list
    of rejected applications read like error toasts.

  - src/components/DotBadge.jsx — compact badge with neutral
    background + small colored dot indicator. Replaces
    <Badge className='bg-purple-50 text-purple-700 border-purple-200'>
    patterns with <DotBadge color={ROLE_DOT_COLORS.admin}>. One
    badge surface style across the app; semantic distinction via
    dot color.

Five surfaces migrated:

  1. src/pages/LandingPage.jsx
     - Emoji → lucide icons in 44x44 brand-tinted tiles:
         TC:       ClipboardCheck (clipboard + verification)
         Investor: Building2 (real estate, not generic TrendingUp)
         PML:      Landmark (banking institution, not briefcase)
     - Per-card gradient bars (teal-cyan / cyan-blue / teal-green)
       → unified teal accent bar. Differentiation comes from icon
       + role name, not competing color stripes.
     - Trust-bar icons wrapped with Icon for consistent stroke.

  2. src/components/layout/Sidebar.jsx
     - All nav icons migrated through Icon wrapper for thin stroke.
     - Header Menu/ChevronLeft icons (inside the collapsed/expanded
       two-button structure) wrapped.
     - Curated icon picks:
         TC Directory:       Briefcase → UserCheck
         Investor Directory: TrendingUp → Building2
         PML Directory:      DollarSign → Landmark
         Pipeline:           ClipboardList → Layers (was duplicating
                             the Applications icon)
         My Profile (all 4 roles): unified to User, replacing the
                             role-varying Briefcase/Building2/DollarSign.
                             Profile is a profile regardless of role.

  3. src/pages/admin/Members.jsx
     - ROLE_COLORS constant (5 color families) removed.
     - STATUS_COLORS constant (3 color families) removed.
     - Role Badge → DotBadge with ROLE_DOT_COLORS lookup.
     - Status Badge → DotBadge with STATUS_DOT_COLORS lookup.
     - All inline icons (Search, Pencil, Users, ChevronLeft/Right
       pagination) wrapped with Icon.
     - 'Badge' import dropped (no longer used in this file).

  4. src/pages/admin/Applications.jsx
     - Local STATUS_STYLES constant (rainbow) removed.
     - Status Badge → DotBadge.
     - 'NDA ✓' emerald badge → neutral 'NDA signed' badge (kept as
       Badge since no dot semantics; sits alongside DotBadge
       naturally).
     - CheckCircle2, XCircle, Eye, Clock, Building2, MapPin all
       wrapped with Icon.

  5. src/pages/dashboard/AdminDashboard.jsx
     - Unused STATUS_STYLES constant (another rainbow) removed
       (dead code since T2.2f when AdminDashboard was migrated to
       synthetic-app pattern).
     - Stat card icons wrapped — existing gradient-primary tile
       treatment kept as-is (was already on-brand with teal/cobalt
       gradient).
     - Empty state and inline icons (CheckCircle2, Building2,
       MapPin, XCircle) wrapped.

Patch baseline note:
  This PR's Sidebar.jsx hunks are generated against the current
  production structure (two-button Logo+title header). The preflight
  check in the plan verifies this with a grep for
  'title="ALS Deal Connect"'; fail-fast if the Sidebar structure
  has diverged.

What's deliberately NOT in scope (follow-ups):

  - ServiceRequest status badges (RequestList, RequestDetail) —
    REQUEST_STATUS_DOT_COLORS is defined in roleStyles.js ready for
    a later migration. Skipped here because those pages use their
    own STATUS_COLORS map imported from serviceRequestUtils.js;
    migrating properly means updating the shared util and every
    downstream site in one sweep. Separate, focused PR.
  - Deal stage badges on DealCard (Under Contract / Pre-Close /
    Closing Soon) — contextual deal-state rather than member/status,
    arguably benefits from the color-coding. Leave alone.
  - Review stars — kept amber. Universal UX convention; five
    stars in brand teal would confuse users.
  - Dashboard status badges in TCDashboard / PMLDashboard — lower
    traffic, same pattern available via DotBadge when touched.

Verification:

  - npm run lint: 0 errors (full codebase)
  - Scoped lint: 0 errors, 4 pre-existing warnings (unused catch
    params, unused user prop) not introduced by this PR
  - npm run build: succeeds
  - No user-facing functional changes — role-filtering, status
    transitions, edit flows all preserved exactly

